Week 07 - Regression

Linear Regression

Last week we looked at correlation, which gives us a normalized representation of how well to datasets covary, but what if we wanted to model that relationship, or even use it for prediction.

Ordinary linear regression

OLR is a simple way to create a linear model of that relates one or more vectors (X) to a target data series (Y). Lets use the airquality dataset to explore this.

rr X=airquality\(Wind Y=airquality\)Ozone toRemove=which(is.na(X) | is.na(Y)) X=X[-toRemove] Y=Y[-toRemove] plot(X,Y)

In regression, we will refer to X as the design matrix. This is the matrix of predictors. It must have the same number of rows as Y, but can have any number of columns. The number of columns will correspond to the number of coefficients in the model. We represent these coefficients in a column vector that has as many rows as there are columns in X.

Lets make our design matrix. It will be Wind, plus a column of ones so we can get a Y intercept in our model.

rr ones=matrix(1,nrow=length(X)) length(X)

[1] 116

rr Xd=cbind(ones,X) #this is our design matrix

Linear algebra doesnt love NAs, lets make sure weve removed them all.

rr any(is.na(Xd))

[1] FALSE

Remember that in OLS, were trying to minimize the sum of squares of the residuals, or the error, which we call E.

\(Y = Xb + E\)

Where Y is a column of predictands, X is our design matrix, b is our column of coefficients, and E is the error, the difference between Xb and Y. We want to find b that makes the sum of squares in E as small as possible.

We refered to the derivation of this on the board, and will now use the result of this, called the Normal equation to find b, that minimize the sum of squares if E.

rr #Use normal equation (XX)-1 * (XY) XX=t(Xd)%%Xd XY=t(Xd)%%Y B=solve(XX)%*%XY print(B)

       [,1]
  96.872895
X -5.550923

OK. That was easy, now we have our model. Lets see how well it works.

Lets use the model to calculate predicted Y over the interval 0 to 20.

rr xseq=seq(0,20) yhat=xseq*B[2]+B[1] #just calculating it as a simple y=mx+b type equation. #now lets plot the original data, and add a line for our model. library(ggplot2) regPlot = ggplot()+geom_point(aes(X,Y))+geom_line(aes(xseq,yhat)) print(regPlot)

Rather than calculating Yhat the slow way by spelling out the linear equation, we can do it simply using the design matrix, to model the values present in X. Or creating a new design matrix to model any range in X.

Remember, our equation was \(Y = Xb + E\) so \(\hat{Y} = Xb\)

The difference between Y and Yhat is our E. Its also called the residuals. Lets take a look at our residuals.

rr residuals = Y-yhat2 ggplot()+geom_point(aes(X,residuals)) #as a line plot

rr ggplot()+geom_histogram(aes(X)) #as a histogram

Uncertainty in our regression model

Our model is not a perfect representation of reality, and wed like to estimate the uncertainty on our parameters in B. Were going to base this on the residuals.

First we need to calculate the root mean squared error (RMSE) of our residuals:

rr SSE = t(residuals)%*%residuals MSE = SSE / (length(Y)-length(B)) #the degrees of freedom here is the number of observations minus the number of parameters we calculated #Now moving forward we want the root mean square error (RMSE) or s . s = sqrt(MSE) print(s)

         [,1]
[1,] 26.46729

OK, now that we have an estimate of \(\sigma\) for our residuals, we can use that to find the covariance matrix of B, like this:

rr #Now, lets use s to calculate uncertainty on B #Find the covariance of B. Using this equation covB = solve(t(Xd)%%Xd)as.vector(s^2) print(covB)

                     X
  52.398615 -4.7008056
X -4.700806  0.4766551

This is the covariance matrix of B, and the standard error of B is the square root of the diagonal:

rr stdB = diag(sqrt(covB))

NaNs produced

rr print(stdB)

                  X 
7.2386887 0.6904021

OK, now lets calculate some line that show the uncertainty in our model. Well show one standard error. This means that our regression parameters could be higher or lower than we calculated. So well calculate some new \(\hat{Y}\) values for hi and low values.

rr #OK now calculate lines that correspond to the uncertainty yhatHi = Xd%%(B+stdB) yhatLo = Xd%%(B-stdB)

Now lets add those to our plot.

Lastly, what if we want to estimate the uncertainty on certain prediction?

Just create a desing matrix for that prediction!

rr X5 = c(1, 5)#Create a single value design matrix to make a prediction pred = X5%%B#multiply that matrix by B to get you modeled prediction pred.unc = X5%%stdB#multiply that matrix by std error of B to get uncertainty on prediction

If we assume that prediction is normal, with a mean of the prediction and a standard deviation of the probability, whats probability in our prediction that if the wind is blowing 5 mph, the ozone concentration will be above 80?

Lets make a plot to visualize what were testing:

And then we can use pnorm to calculate the area right of 80

rr 1-pnorm(80,mean = pred,sd = pred.unc)

[1] 0.1543704
